# 12 - Log-regression

# the fact that we have an x variable that is binominal, that is also have an impact on y, a change of 1 in this variable have a lot of weight (the precdictor is -0.61). theres a problem here - in total there are 333 defaults, even if we assume (inccorectly) that all defaults made by students, that makes less than 12% of students. that means that the predictor of students got stronger impact than it deserves - probably because the value is binominal.
# we can see that balance has negative effect on the probability of default, and income has a non-significant negative effect.

# d, e
log_pred <- predict(log_reg, newdata = x_test, type = "response")
summary(log_pred)
##      Min.   1st Qu.    Median      Mean   3rd Qu.      Max. 
## 0.0000085 0.0002428 0.0018921 0.0330164 0.0128663 0.9719048
plot(log_pred, main = "Logistic Prediction", ylab = "predicted probability" ,col = "purple")

# the results are between 0 to 1, as logistic predicion should be. we can see that the first three quantiles are lower than 0.16, which isnt surprising since the rate of defulting in the data is 0.033. we can decide on a threshold, e.g. x>0.033, to decide if a specific person defaulted/will default.

# f
calssifier <- ifelse(log_pred>0.033, "Yes", "No")

#g, h
table(calssifier, y_test) #confusion matrix
##           y_test
## calssifier   No  Yes
##        No  2510   17
##        Yes  390   83
mean(calssifier==y_test) #accuracy
## [1] 0.8643333
# we got 2470 true-positive (people who will not default) is above to 85%. false-negative - we have a big number of people who the will be rejected eve though they will be able to pay off, but maybe 15% is not bad since it is more important to get more accuracy on the true-negative. we checked a few different threshold, and concluded that the value that represents the default-rate in the population was a good threshold.

# c
lda_pred <- predict(lda_model, newdata = x_test)
# d
names(lda_pred)
## [1] "class"     "posterior" "x"
hist(lda_pred$x, main = "Histogram of LDA", xlab="prediction in LD1")

summary(lda_pred$class)
##   No  Yes 
## 2966   34
?predict.lda
# Predict function return 3 different components. 
# (1) class is the prediction for if that observation will default or not; 
# (2) posterior is the probability for defaulting or not per observation;
# (3) 'x' is the value in the new dimension (LD1) per observation, it seems that 'class' is set based on a threshold that was calculated from these values, that sets if a certain observation will be categorised as non-default or default. 

# e
lda_probs <- lda_pred$posterior[,"Yes"]
table(lda_pred$class, y_test) #confusion matrix
##      y_test
##         No  Yes
##   No  2894   72
##   Yes    6   28
mean(lda_pred$class == y_test) #accuracy
## [1] 0.974
# f
# the model has high false-negative rate. 3/4 out of the observations who defaulted were assumed to not default, which is costly for lenders/bank. the accuracy is 97.1%, the model might be a bit too much affected by the size of the 'no' group.

# 17 - running PCA
pca_model <- prcomp(dat, scale=TRUE)
# b
?prcomp
#pca_model
labels(pca_model)
## [1] "sdev"     "rotation" "center"   "scale"    "x"
# we'll try to understand sdev
ve <- pca_model$sdev^2 # variance explained
pve <- ve/sum(ve) # proportion variance explained
cpve <- cumsum(pve) # cumulative proportion variance explained
plot(pve, type="o", main = "proportion of variance explained", xlab = "component index", ylab = "variance explained")

plot(cpve, type="o", main = "cumulative proportion of variance explained", xlab = "number of components", ylab = "variance explained")

# (1) sdev - the standard deviation (Root of the variance), we can see that it is ordered from the most explanatory to the least;
# (2) 'x' is the size of explained variance in each Principal Component.
# (3) rotation is the matrix of the eigenvectors; 
# (4) center is the vector of the centers for each of the PCs
# (5) scale is the proportion we divided by to get all vectors to be proportional to each other 

#c
plot(x=pca_model$x[,1], y=pca_model$x[,2], main = "First Two Principal Components", xlab = "PC1", ylab = "PC2")

#d
cols <- rainbow(length(unique(labs)))
obs_cols <- cols[as.numeric(as.factor(labs))]

# plotting the first two PCs
plot(x=pca_model$x[,1], y=pca_model$x[,2], col = obs_cols, main = "First Two Principal Components", xlab = "PC1", ylab = "PC2")

# we can see that the first PC is able to seperate some of the groups (green, yellow, blue) but can't distinguishe some of them (blue from bright-blue, pink, purple...), and the second PC seperate one more (blue from light-blue) but not helping with some (e.g. pink and purple).

# 18 - Hierarchical Clustering
#a
scaled_dat <- scale(dat)
#b
dist_dat <- dist(scaled_dat, method = "euclidian")

#c
hc_model <- hclust(dist_dat, method = "complete")
# d
plot(hc_model, labels=labs)

# e
hc_clusters <- cutree(hc_model, k=5)
# we chose k=5 because the we saw based on the dendrogram that 5 clusters seemes like a stable division. we could have chosen k=14 because we have 14 types of cancer in the data, it does not look like the HC model would have good predictions in this situation (large variance). 

# 19 - K-means
# a
# run k-means
set.seed(0) 
KM <- kmeans(scaled_dat, centers = 6)

# b
?kmeans
#str(KM)
# (1) clusters - the final allocation of each observation to a cluster;
# (2) centers - the final center-point of each cluster;
# (3) totss - the sum of distances between each observation to each other observation;
# (4) withinss - the sum of the distances in each cluster between points;
# (5) tot.withinss - the sum of sums of the distances in each cluster between points;
# (6) betweenss - the sum of distances between each of the clusters;
# (7) size - number of observations in each cluster
# (8) iter - number of iterations (how many times repeated the loop: [1] allocate each point by the center-point that is closest to; [2] calculating new mean to the clusters' center-pints)

# c
WithinSS <- KM$withinss
BetweenSS <- KM$betweenss

as.data.frame(WithinSS)
as.data.frame(BetweenSS)
# it seemes like cluster 3 have very big variance (big distances between points within the cluster), whereas cluster 4 for example is very tight. the betweenSS is a bit larger than the withinSS of the third cluster, but marginally higher than the rest of the sums which seems good on the whole.

clusterAllocation <- as.data.frame(KM$cluster)
hist(KM$cluster, breaks = 18 ,main = "frequency per cluster", xlab = "cluster", col = c(rainbow(17)))

# plot clusters on first two PCs
par(mfcol = c(1,2))
plot(x=pca_model$x[,1], y=pca_model$x[,2], col = obs_cols, main = "True Classification", xlab = "PC1", ylab = "PC2") #for comparison
plot(x=pca_model$x[,1], y=pca_model$x[,2], col = KM$cluster+1, main = "K-Mean Classification", xlab = "PC1", ylab = "PC2")

# we got the same PC graph, but now the colors indicate the classes predicted by the K-means method. with comparing this to the results from the above graph (where the colors were given directly from the data) we can see that the k-means worked pretty well, but not perfect.
